CC and tryptophol at a concentration of 1 × 10-4 M were chosen as the objects of study and were introduced into the N, S-GQDs/K2S2O8 system. The current and ECL intensity experienced a pronounced reduction at the maximum voltage of 1.7 V in the CV scan range (Fig. 4
                        ), indicating that CC or tryptophol had a quenching effect on the paper-based ECL system. Fig. 4. (b) and Fig. 4. (d) showed that there was no ECL signal for N, S-GQDs when the electrode potential was scanned from 0 V to 1.0 V. At low voltage conditions, the generation of N, S-GQDs•− and SO4
                        •− is limited, and the low-voltage environment is unfavorable for sustaining their states, the entire system did not reach an energetically sufficient state. Therefore, no ECL was observed at 0–1 V [52,53]. And the starting potential for light emission was about 1.2 V. After adding CC or tryptophol, the starting potential for light emission significantly shifted to the right and the ECL intensity decreased. The observed reduction in peak current and ECL intensity in this system indicates that both CC and tryptophol can impede the electron transfer between the electrode and the N, S-GQDs/K2S2O8 system, leading to a consequent decrease in the sensor's ECL intensity. To systematically investigate the electrochemical processes of CC and tryptophol in the reaction system, we employed higher concentrations of CC and tryptophol (10-3 M) to specifically study their CV curves. As depicted in Fig. 4. (e) and (f), CC exhibited a distinct oxidation peak at 0.6 V, while tryptophol displayed an oxidation peak around 0.85 V, confirming their oxidation phenomena in this electrochemical system, this also results in an increase in current in the voltage range of 0.6–1.2 V, as observed in Fig. 4(a)(c). This refined analysis provides a deeper insight into the electrochemical behavior of CC and tryptophol within the studied system.
